If a lowercased JIRA issue key is mentioned in the commit message, when you hover it on the Activity Stream it'll show an 'Issue not found' error in the popup.

I have a JIRA issue TEST-1, and I committed the changeset with this message: {{test-1, fixed it}}

When I hover this issue key in the FishEye activity stream after the incremental indexing process runs:
* This is thrown in the logs:
{noformat}
2012-02-22 16:34:59,380 WARN  [btpool0-21 ] fisheye.app com.cenqua.fisheye.logging.Logs-logWarningWithDetailToDebug - Error retrieving issue 'test-1' from JIRA server at http://localhost:8080/browse/test-1: com.atlassian.crucible.spi.services.NotPermittedException: com.atlassian.jira.rpc.exception.RemotePermissionException: This issue does not exist or you don't have permission to view it. (enable debug logging for more details)
{noformat}
* The popup displayed shows 'Issue not found'.

This error is not reproducible when I hover another commit message where the same JIRA issue key is uppercased.

The check for {noformat}if (!isStopRequested() && LuceneIndexes.METADATA_VERSION != cache.getMetadataVersion()){noformat} will never be true. See ths comment above it:
{noformat}

        // I don't think this ever gets called - this is superseded by the call to RepositoryEngine.resetRepositoryMetadataIndex() in RepositoryEngine.start()
        // RepositoryEngine.resetRepositoryMetadataIndex() is a super-set of upgradeMetadataIndex(). Delete this code after 2.7.11, as I'd like to let the delete of this be
        // dog-fooded longer than 1 day and preferably not by OnDemand first! RepositoryEngine.start() alsos ets the indexingPhase to metadata, so even if there are no
        // revisions, it will still upgrade the Metadata and content immediately.

{noformat}

Check this is true for all repo types and remove the unused code.

Would it be possible to link to git commits if the hash is included in a commit message? For example, when a commit is reverted using {{git revert}}, the default commit message created by git includes:

{quote}
This reverts commit 320e76b6d416de1aebb0276e170fe31cfdb6400b.
{quote}

It would be nice if the Fisheye interface linked this hash to the previous commit. It should be fairly easy to detect commit hashes as a hexidecimal string of a certain length (even if only full-length hashes are detected, although it would be nice if truncated ones were linked too).

Another possible use case is where one commit relates to a previous commit - the new commit can include the hash of the related commit in its commit message.

The PHP syntax highlighting was incorrectly matching keywords when they appeared at the end of a function name. For example, when displaying "trigger_error(…)", the "or" at the end of the function name was highlighted as a keyword.

I've fixed this in our syntax highlighting by adding \\b to the *beginning* of the regexp as well as the end:

{quote}
/\b(abstract|and|array|as|break|case|catch|cfunction|class|clone|const|continue|declare|default|do|else|elseif|enddeclare|endfor|endforeach|endif|endswitch|endwhile|extends|final|for|foreach|function|global|goto|if|implements|interface|instanceof|namespace|new|old_function|or|private|protected|public|static|switch|throw|try|use|var|while|xor|__CLASS__|__DIR__|__FILE__|__FUNCTION__|__METHOD__|__NAMESPACE__|die|exit|eval|include|include_once|require|require_once|return)\b/
{quote}

As described on the [documentation of Smart Commits|http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/FISHEYE/Using+Smart+Commits] is possible to specify:

{noformat}
<n>w <n>d <n>h <n>m <work log comment> where <n> is a user-specified time period.
{noformat}

And the given example goes:

{code}
#time 1w 2d 4h 30m Total work logged — this command would record 1 week, 2 days, 4hours and 30 minutes against an issue, and add the comment 'Total work logged' in the Work Log tab of the issue.
{code}

Expected:

The issue should have the work log saved with the proper time. Not only with the first part of the time expression.

