I added a REST point for Studio/OnDemand so that we could fire a reindex and wait.

If the indexer fails while doing an intial index (in this case, because the path inside the SVN repo was invalid) the RepositoryStatus object is set so that doneFullSlurp is false (correctly) and it has an engine error.

When the RepositoryIndexingStatus is built (in DefaultrepositoryIndexer.getIndexingStatus()), it translates "donFullSlurp==false && engine.wantInitialSlurp()" as fullInexInProgress. This is ambiguous in the case where an error occurred.

The workaround is to also check RepositoryIndexingStatus.hasEngineError() and bail out if that is the case.

The failing code in the plugin is below:
{code}
private void reindexRepository(String repository) throws RepositoryConfigException
    {
        log.debug("Requested reindex on " + repository);
        RepositoryIndexer indexer = repositoryAdminService.getIndexer(repository);
        indexer.startFullReindexing();
        
        while(indexer.getIndexingStatus().isFullIndexingInProgress())
        {
            try
            {
                Thread.sleep(100); // 100ms == 1/10th of a second
            }
            catch (InterruptedException e)
            {
                log.error("Thread interrupted while waiting for reindex", e);
            }
        }
    }
{code}

The isFullIndexingInProgress call always returns true, even after 10-20 minutes.

Nothing in the UI indicated that FishEye was actually indexing. It did report the invalid repository path.

As far as I can tell this doesn't have any user-visible consequences in the ui, its just reported as a javascript error.

This seems to be fixed by jquery 1.7.1 --- we're currently using jquery 1.5.2

minified: jquery-min.js line 1 character 26151
unminified: jquery.js line 2210 character 5

jquery 1.5.2
{code}
if ( !eventHandle ) {
			elemData.handle = eventHandle = function( e ) {
				// Handle the second event of a trigger and when
				// an event is called after a page has unloaded
				return typeof jQuery !== "undefined" && jQuery.event.triggered !== e.type ?
					jQuery.event.handle.apply( eventHandle.elem, arguments ) :
					undefined;
			};
		}
{code}

jquery 1.7.1:
{code}
if ( !eventHandle ) {
			elemData.handle = eventHandle = function( e ) {
				// Discard the second event of a jQuery.event.trigger() and
				// when an event is called after a page has unloaded
				return typeof jQuery !== "undefined" && (!e || jQuery.event.triggered !== e.type) ?
					jQuery.event.dispatch.apply( eventHandle.elem, arguments ) :
					undefined;
			};
			// Add elem as a property of the handle fn to prevent a memory leak with IE non-native events
			eventHandle.elem = elem;
		}
{code}
